    <question>
        <prompt>William Doak, Hoover's Secretary of Labor, was known for:</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Supporting immigration reform</option>
            <option letter="b">Aggressive deportation of Mexican immigrants</option>
            <option letter="c">Protecting workers' rights</option>
            <option letter="d">Promoting labor unions</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>William Doak, as Secretary of Labor during the Hoover administration, initiated aggressive deportation campaigns targeting Mexican immigrants. During the early years of the Great Depression, he claimed this would create more jobs for American citizens. His actions led to the forced repatriation of hundreds of thousands of Mexican and Mexican-American people, including many U.S. citizens.</explanation>
    </question>
